Lets visualize a few of the variables.

First, Lando. Lets start by printing out the first 5 values.

head(dataset$LandoAttitude)
[1] Unfamiliar (N/A)                                                                       
[3] Unfamiliar (N/A)                            Somewhat favorably                         
[5] Neither favorably nor unfavorably (neutral) Neither favorably nor unfavorably (neutral)
7 Levels:  Neither favorably nor unfavorably (neutral) Somewhat favorably Somewhat unfavorably ... Very unfavorably

Two problems pop out.

  1. There are Unfamiliar (N/A) values and blank values. We need to remove those.
  2. All the values are words. Wed like to work with numbers. We need to recode the values.

The easiest way to work with numbers is to realize that the levels are ordered. Theyre just ordered alphabetically instead of according to the ranks wed like to use. Lets reorder the levels so that:

  1. Very unfavorably
  2. Somewhat unfavorably
  3. Neither favorably nor unfavorably
  4. Somewhat favorably
  5. Very favorably
  6. Unfamiliar (N/A)
dataset$LandoAttitude = factor(dataset$LandoAttitude,levels(dataset$LandoAttitude)[c(7,4,2,3,6,5,1)])
print(levels(dataset$LandoAttitude))
[1] "Very unfavorably"                            "Somewhat unfavorably"                       
[3] "Neither favorably nor unfavorably (neutral)" "Somewhat favorably"                         
[5] "Very favorably"                              "Unfamiliar (N/A)"                           
[7] ""

Now the levels are ordered how wed like. Now, lets replace Unfamiliar with NA. NA is the official data missing symbol in R.

dataset$LandoAttitude <- ifelse(dataset$LandoAttitude == "Unfamiliar (N/A)", c(NA), c(dataset$LandoAttitude))

If we look at the data, Unfamiliar (N/A)" has been replaced with NA. But every other value has been replaced with its number. So all we have to do now, is replace 7 with NA (because was reordered to be 7)
